Following the discovery of the first suspected case of Coronavirus in Katsina State, governors of the states in North-West of Nigeria have announced the closure of all schools in the zone. The governors, after a closed-door meeting held in Kaduna on Wednesday, said the closure was for 30 days. They said that the measure had become imperative in order to prevent the spread of the COVID-19 pandemic in the zone. Chairman of the forum, who is also the Katsina State Governor, Aminu Masari, read the communique shortly after the closed-door meeting. Masari said the schools would be closed down from Monday, 23rd of March 2020. He said that the governors of the individual states in the zone would meet with examination boards to discuss the closure of the schools. The governors also enjoined the members of the public in the zone to avoid unnecessary gatherings and also advised them to maintain good respiratory hygiene. The governors of the meeting included those of Katsina, Zamfara, Sokoto, Jigawa, Kebbi, Kaduna and Niger states. Kano State Governor Abdullahi Ganduje was represented by his deputy, Nasiru Gawuna. 